INSERT INTO questions
  (id, specialty, stem, choices, correct_answer, explanation, telemetry, domain_name, subtopic, difficulty, "references", status, category)
VALUES
('authored-batch-r20-037', 'Regional & Pain', 'A 64-year-old man with severe COPD (FEV1 42% predicted, baseline room-air SpO2 of 92%) presents for arthroscopic rotator cuff repair of the left shoulder. The attending proposes a single-shot ultrasound-guided interscalene brachial plexus block with 20 mL of 0.5% ropivacaine for surgical anesthesia and analgesia. The student anesthetist is concerned about a specific predictable physiologic effect of this block in this patient. Which statement best characterizes the risk that should most influence the anesthetic plan?', '[{"text":"Phrenic nerve involvement is rare with ultrasound guidance, so no pulmonary precautions are needed","label":"A","correct":false,"rationale":"Incorrect; although ultrasound and lower volumes reduce the incidence, phrenic spread remains very common and cannot be assumed absent."},{"text":"Ipsilateral hemidiaphragmatic paresis is nearly universal and may not be tolerated given his limited pulmonary reserve","label":"B","correct":true,"rationale":"Correct; phrenic nerve spread causes hemidiaphragmatic paresis in close to 100% of standard interscalene blocks, which can precipitate respiratory decompensation in a patient with severe COPD."},{"text":"The primary concern is contralateral diaphragm paralysis causing bilateral respiratory failure","label":"C","correct":false,"rationale":"Incorrect; the block affects the ipsilateral phrenic nerve only, producing unilateral, not bilateral, diaphragmatic dysfunction."},{"text":"Recurrent laryngeal nerve block will cause complete airway obstruction in most patients","label":"D","correct":false,"rationale":"Incorrect; recurrent laryngeal involvement causes hoarseness and is usually well tolerated, and it is not the dominant respiratory risk of this block."},{"text":"The block reliably improves his vital capacity by relieving shoulder splinting","label":"E","correct":false,"rationale":"Incorrect; interscalene block does not augment vital capacity and in fact typically reduces it by roughly 25-30% through diaphragmatic paresis."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Because the phrenic nerve lies on the anterior scalene muscle immediately adjacent to the brachial plexus at the interscalene level, anterior spread of local anesthetic produces ipsilateral hemidiaphragmatic paresis in nearly all standard-volume interscalene blocks, reducing vital capacity by about 25-30%. Patients with severe COPD or other marginal pulmonary reserve may not tolerate this and can decompensate. Lower local anesthetic volumes, more distal injection, or alternative blocks (e.g., superior trunk or supraclavicular approaches) reduce but do not eliminate the risk, so the technique should be reconsidered in this patient.', '{}'::jsonb, 'Subspecialty Care', 'Upper extremity blocks: interscalene block and phrenic nerve/respiratory effects', 'medium', '[{"url":"https://www.openanesthesia.org/keywords/interscalene-block/","source":"Interscalene Block"}]'::jsonb, 'sme_review', 'Regional & Pain'),
('authored-batch-r20-038', 'Cardiac', 'A 68-year-old woman is separating from cardiopulmonary bypass after a 3-vessel coronary artery bypass graft. As protamine is administered to reverse heparin (1 mg per 100 units), the surgeon notes the heart distending and the field becoming engorged; arterial pressure falls from 92/54 to 41/26 mmHg, central venous pressure rises to 22 mmHg, and the pulmonary artery pressure climbs sharply. There is no rash or bronchospasm. What is the most appropriate immediate management?', '[{"text":"Continue the protamine and give a 20% lipid emulsion bolus over 2-3 minutes","label":"A","correct":false,"rationale":"Lipid emulsion treats local anesthetic systemic toxicity, not a protamine reaction, and continuing protamine would worsen the pulmonary vasoconstriction."},{"text":"Administer a large fluid bolus and place the patient in steep Trendelenburg","label":"B","correct":false,"rationale":"Aggressive volume into an acutely failing, pressure-overloaded right ventricle would further distend it and worsen failure rather than treat the underlying pulmonary vasoconstriction."},{"text":"Stop the protamine infusion, return to full cardiopulmonary bypass support, and re-heparinize","label":"C","correct":true,"rationale":"Correct: this picture is a catastrophic protamine reaction with acute pulmonary vasoconstriction and right-heart failure, and the safest rescue is to stop protamine, re-establish bypass for hemodynamic support, and re-heparinize for the circuit."},{"text":"Give a rapid bolus of additional protamine to ensure complete heparin neutralization","label":"D","correct":false,"rationale":"More protamine intensifies the very reaction causing pulmonary hypertension and right-heart failure and is contraindicated."},{"text":"Administer intravenous phenylephrine alone and continue weaning from bypass","label":"E","correct":false,"rationale":"Phenylephrine can raise systemic pressure but does not address the catastrophic pulmonary vasoconstriction and right ventricular distention, and proceeding off bypass risks arrest."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Protamine can cause a spectrum of reactions; the most feared is a Type III catastrophic pulmonary vasoconstriction with acute right ventricular failure, recognized by rising CVP/PA pressures, RV distention, and systemic hypotension as protamine is given. Management is to stop the protamine, re-heparinize, and resume cardiopulmonary bypass to support the circulation while the reaction is treated (pulmonary vasodilators, inotropes). Slowing or pausing protamine administration and giving it through a peripheral line over 10-15 minutes can reduce the risk of these reactions.', '{}'::jsonb, 'Subspecialty Care', 'Protamine reactions and pulmonary vasoconstriction during separation from cardiopulmonary bypass', 'hard', '[{"url":"https://www.openanesthesia.org/keywords/protamine-reactions/","source":"Protamine Reactions (OpenAnesthesia)"}]'::jsonb, 'sme_review', 'Cardiac'),
('authored-batch-r20-039', 'Cardiac', 'A 58-year-old man with metastatic lung cancer presents for an urgent subxiphoid pericardial window. He is dyspneic and anxious, sitting upright. Vitals: HR 122/min, BP 88/64 mmHg with a 16 mmHg pulsus paradoxus, distended neck veins, and muffled heart sounds. Echocardiography shows a large circumferential pericardial effusion with right atrial systolic collapse and a plethoric inferior vena cava. The surgeon requests general anesthesia. Which anesthetic plan best matches the hemodynamic goals for this patient before the pericardium is opened?', '[{"text":"Induce with a high-dose propofol bolus and immediately initiate controlled positive-pressure ventilation","label":"A","correct":false,"rationale":"High-dose propofol drops preload and afterload while positive-pressure ventilation further reduces venous return, a combination that can precipitate cardiovascular collapse in tamponade."},{"text":"Perform a slow neuraxial-based technique to lower systemic vascular resistance and afterload","label":"B","correct":false,"rationale":"Reducing SVR is exactly the wrong goal in tamponade, where maintaining afterload and preload is essential, and neuraxial sympathectomy could cause collapse."},{"text":"Deepen anesthesia with high-dose volatile agent to blunt the tachycardia before incision","label":"C","correct":false,"rationale":"Deliberately slowing the compensatory tachycardia and adding the vasodilation/myocardial depression of high-dose volatile agent removes the patient''s primary compensatory mechanisms."},{"text":"Prep and drape awake, maintain spontaneous ventilation, and induce with ketamine while preserving preload, heart rate, and afterload","label":"D","correct":true,"rationale":"Correct: the goals are ''full, fast, and tight'' — maintain preload, heart rate, and SVR — and preparing the patient before induction with a hemodynamically stable agent like ketamine that preserves sympathetic tone and spontaneous ventilation is the safest approach."},{"text":"Administer a beta-blocker to control the heart rate and reduce myocardial oxygen demand","label":"E","correct":false,"rationale":"In tamponade, fixed stroke volume makes cardiac output rate-dependent, so blunting the compensatory tachycardia with a beta-blocker can cause profound hypotension."}]'::jsonb, 'D', 'In cardiac tamponade, stroke volume is fixed and low, so cardiac output depends on maintaining a relatively high heart rate, adequate preload, and adequate afterload — summarized as ''full, fast, and tight.'' Induction of general anesthesia and positive-pressure ventilation are the highest-risk moments because they reduce venous return and abolish sympathetic compensation, which can cause arrest before the pericardium is decompressed. Prepping/draping the patient awake and using a hemodynamically stable agent such as ketamine while preserving spontaneous ventilation, with surgical decompression ready, is the preferred approach.', '{}'::jsonb, 'Subspecialty Care', 'Cardiac tamponade physiology and induction hemodynamics (full, fast, tight)', 'medium', '[{"url":"https://www.openanesthesia.org/keywords/cardiac-tamponade-anesth-management/","source":"Cardiac Tamponade (OpenAnesthesia)"}]'::jsonb, 'sme_review', 'Cardiac'),
('authored-batch-r20-040', 'Monitoring, Equipment & Physiology', 'During setup for a general anesthetic, a CAA hangs what is labeled as an oxygen E-cylinder on the right-hand hanger yoke of the anesthesia machine. The cylinder seats fully and the valve opens, but the CAA notices the yoke pins did not engage any holes and a Bodok seal was not in place. The Pin Index Safety System uses two pins per gas placed in a semicircular arc, with oxygen assigned positions 2 and 5. Which of the following BEST explains how a cylinder containing a hypoxic gas could nonetheless be seated and delivered through this oxygen yoke?', '[{"text":"The Bodok seal itself carries the indexing holes, so omitting it bypasses the pin index","label":"A","correct":false,"rationale":"Incorrect: the Bodok seal is only a sealing washer between valve and yoke and plays no role in gas-specific indexing."},{"text":"Oxygen pin positions 2 and 5 are shared with nitrous oxide, so the two cylinders are interchangeable at the yoke","label":"B","correct":false,"rationale":"Incorrect: nitrous oxide is assigned positions 3 and 5, a different pin pattern, so it cannot normally seat on an oxygen yoke when pins are intact."},{"text":"The Diameter Index Safety System on the yoke failed, allowing the pins to retract","label":"C","correct":false,"rationale":"Incorrect: the Diameter Index Safety System applies to threaded low-pressure pipeline connections, not to the pin-indexed high-pressure hanger yoke."},{"text":"E-cylinders are too small to engage the pin index, which functions only on large H-cylinders","label":"D","correct":false,"rationale":"Incorrect: the pin index system is specifically the safeguard for small cylinders on hanger yokes, whereas large H-cylinders use threaded (DISS-type) connections at the manifold."},{"text":"The pins on the yoke were removed or broken off, allowing a non-indexed valve to seat fully","label":"E","correct":true,"rationale":"Correct: missing or broken yoke pins defeat the Pin Index Safety System, permitting a cylinder of any gas to seat and flow, which is a recognized cause of wrong-gas delivery."}]'::jsonb, 'E', 'The Pin Index Safety System prevents wrong-gas connection by requiring two yoke pins to mate with two correspondingly drilled holes on the cylinder valve, with each gas assigned a unique pin pattern (oxygen 2,5; nitrous oxide 3,5; air 1,5). The system is defeated only when the yoke pins are missing, bent, or broken, or when extra Bodok seals are stacked to lift the valve off the pins; either allows a non-matching valve to seat and flow. The Bodok seal is purely a gas-tight washer and provides no indexing. Recognizing that a cylinder seated without pin engagement is unsafe should prompt immediate removal before any case proceeds.', '{}'::jsonb, 'Subspecialty Care', 'Medical gas supply and cylinder safety (Pin Index Safety System)', 'hard', '[{"url":"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK532908/","source":"Pin Index Safety System (StatPearls, NCBI Bookshelf)"}]'::jsonb, 'sme_review', 'Monitoring, Equipment & Physiology'),
('authored-batch-r20-041', 'Monitoring, Equipment & Physiology', 'A 64-year-old man is undergoing laparoscopic sigmoid colectomy under general endotracheal anesthesia with volume-controlled ventilation. Forty minutes into the case, with no change in ventilator settings or surgical CO2 insufflation, the end-tidal CO2 abruptly falls from 38 mm Hg to 6 mm Hg over two breaths and the waveform nearly flattens. The pulse oximeter plethysmograph becomes dampened, the blood pressure is now unobtainable by the cuff, and the arterial line traces a narrow, low pulse pressure. Breath sounds are present bilaterally and the circuit is intact with normal peak airway pressures. Which is the MOST likely explanation for this sudden drop in end-tidal CO2?', '[{"text":"Acute reduction in cardiac output (cardiovascular collapse) reducing pulmonary blood flow","label":"A","correct":true,"rationale":"Correct: a sudden fall in EtCO2 with preserved bilateral breath sounds, intact circuit, and normal airway pressures alongside loss of pulse pressure points to abruptly reduced pulmonary perfusion delivering less CO2 to the alveoli."},{"text":"Esophageal intubation","label":"B","correct":false,"rationale":"Incorrect: esophageal intubation produces an absent or rapidly vanishing waveform from the start of ventilation, not a sudden mid-case drop after 40 minutes of normal capnography."},{"text":"Breathing-circuit disconnection at the Y-piece","label":"C","correct":false,"rationale":"Incorrect: a disconnection would also abolish chest rise, trigger low-pressure/apnea alarms, and drop peak airway pressures, none of which are present here."},{"text":"Acute bronchospasm","label":"D","correct":false,"rationale":"Incorrect: bronchospasm produces a sloping (shark-fin) phase III with rising peak airway pressures and wheezing, not a near-zero flat waveform with normal airway pressures."},{"text":"Hypoventilation from a leaking endotracheal tube cuff","label":"E","correct":false,"rationale":"Incorrect: a cuff leak causes a loss of tidal volume and audible leak with a gradually altered capnogram, not an abrupt fall to near zero with hemodynamic collapse."}]'::jsonb, 'A', 'End-tidal CO2 depends on adequate alveolar ventilation AND pulmonary blood flow to deliver CO2 to the alveoli. When ventilation and the circuit are demonstrably intact (bilateral breath sounds, normal peak pressures, no disconnect alarm) but EtCO2 abruptly collapses with simultaneous loss of pulse pressure, the unifying cause is a sudden fall in cardiac output and thus pulmonary perfusion. This pattern is the capnographic hallmark of cardiovascular collapse (including massive pulmonary or gas embolism and cardiac arrest) and should trigger an immediate hemodynamic and ACLS-oriented response rather than an airway troubleshooting sequence.', '{}'::jsonb, 'Subspecialty Care', 'Capnography / end-tidal CO2 waveform interpretation', 'medium', '[{"url":"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK539754/","source":"Capnography and Respiratory Monitoring (StatPearls, NCBI Bookshelf)"}]'::jsonb, 'sme_review', 'Monitoring, Equipment & Physiology'),
('authored-batch-r20-042', 'Monitoring, Equipment & Physiology', 'A 72-year-old woman with aortic stenosis has a central venous catheter placed for a Whipple procedure. After an uneventful induction she is in normal sinus rhythm and the CVP traces a normal a-c-v pattern with a mean of 8 mm Hg. Midway through the dissection, she develops a regular narrow-complex tachycardia at 130/min; the anesthesia provider notes the P waves are no longer clearly visible on the ECG, the blood pressure falls, and the CVP monitor now shows large, regular pressure spikes occurring with each beat. Which mechanism BEST explains these new giant (cannon) a waves on the CVP tracing?', '[{"text":"Tricuspid regurgitation is producing tall systolic v waves from regurgitant flow into the atrium","label":"A","correct":false,"rationale":"Incorrect: tricuspid regurgitation produces tall v waves with loss of the x descent, not a-wave cannon waves, and would not be newly precipitated simply by a junctional tachycardia."},{"text":"The right atrium is contracting against a closed tricuspid valve because atrial and ventricular contraction are no longer properly sequenced","label":"B","correct":true,"rationale":"Correct: cannon a waves arise when the atrium contracts against a closed tricuspid valve, which occurs in junctional/AV-dissociated rhythms where atrial and ventricular systole coincide, matching the loss of visible P waves and the regular large CVP spikes."},{"text":"Loss of organized atrial contraction has abolished the a wave entirely, as occurs in atrial fibrillation","label":"C","correct":false,"rationale":"Incorrect: this describes absent a waves seen in atrial fibrillation, the opposite of the large regular a waves described."},{"text":"Right ventricular hypertrophy is causing chronically large a waves from impaired ventricular filling","label":"D","correct":false,"rationale":"Incorrect: while RVH can enlarge a waves chronically, it would not appear acutely and synchronously with a new rhythm change and loss of P waves."},{"text":"Catheter whip from the tachycardia is creating artifactual pressure spikes unrelated to atrial mechanics","label":"E","correct":false,"rationale":"Incorrect: catheter whip produces irregular high-frequency artifact, not reproducible large a waves timed to each cardiac cycle with the atrium contracting against a closed valve."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'The CVP a wave reflects right atrial contraction. When atrioventricular synchrony is lost, as in a junctional rhythm or other AV dissociation, the atrium intermittently or regularly contracts while the tricuspid valve is closed, generating a giant retrograde pressure wave known as a cannon a wave. The clinical clues here, a regular narrow-complex tachycardia with loss of visible P waves and new large beat-to-beat CVP spikes, fit a junctional rhythm producing regular cannon waves. Recognizing this is important because the loss of the atrial kick is especially poorly tolerated in a patient with aortic stenosis, explaining the accompanying hypotension.', '{}'::jsonb, 'Subspecialty Care', 'Central venous pressure waveform interpretation', 'hard', '[{"url":"https://www.openanesthesia.org/cvp_waveform_components/","source":"Central Venous Pressure and Pulmonary Artery Wedge Pressure (OpenAnesthesia)"}]'::jsonb, 'sme_review', 'Monitoring, Equipment & Physiology');
